Definition 3.5. For a generating morphism $f$ and a morphism $g$ in a FSSMC, we will write $f\in g$ if $f$ belongs to a decomposition of $g$. In light of Lemma 3.4, uniqueness of decompositions ensures that this definition is correct.
Definition 5.1. A Petri net $(N,{N}_{\mathcal{S}})$ is said to be an identification of $(M,{M}_{\mathcal{S}})$ if there is a morphism $F:(M,{M}_{\mathcal{S}})\to(N,{N}_{\mathcal{S}})$ such that: • There is a Petri net $O$, and a couple transition-preserving functors $l,r:\mathfrak{F}(O)\to\mathfrak{F}(M)$; • $l;{M}_{\mathcal{S}}=r;{M}_{\mathcal{S}}$; • $F$ is the coequalizer of $l$ and $r$. Note that in this case ${N}_{\mathcal{S}}$ coincides with the arrow arising from the universal property of coequalizers. If $(N,{N}_{\mathcal{S}})$ is an identification for $(M,{M}_{\mathcal{S}})$, then we say that $O$, together with $l,r$, is a witness of the identification.
Definition 3.1. Fix a semantics $\mathcal{S}$. We define the category $\textbf{Petri}^{\mathcal{S}}$ as having: • As objects, couples $(N,{N}_{\mathcal{S}})$ where $N$ is a net and ${N}_{\mathcal{S}}:\mathfrak{F}(N)\to\mathcal{S}$ is an assignment of semantics; • Morphisms in $\textbf{Petri}^{\mathcal{S}}[(M,{M}_{\mathcal{S}}),(N,{N}_{\mathcal{S}})]$ consist of all the strict monoidal functors $F:\mathfrak{F}(M)\to\mathfrak{F}(N)$ sending object generators to object generators, and such that ${M}_{\mathcal{S}}=F;{N}_{\mathcal{S}}$; • Identity on $(M,{M}_{\mathcal{S}})$ is the identity functor on $\mathfrak{F}(M)$; • Composition is functor composition. Note how we are in no way requiring that morphisms in $\textbf{Petri}^{\mathcal{S}}$ are transition-preserving. We will often refer to objects of $\textbf{Petri}^{\mathcal{S}}$ just as nets.
Definition 4.1. A net $(M,{M}_{\mathcal{S}})$ is said to be a synchronization of $(N,{N}_{\mathcal{S}})$ if there is a morphism $F:(M,{M}_{\mathcal{S}})\to(N,{N}_{\mathcal{S}})$ such that: • $F$ is injective on generating objects; • $F$ is faithful. • For each generating morphism $f$ of $\mathfrak{F}(N)$, there is a generating morphism $g$ of $\mathfrak{F}(M)$ such that $f\in Fg$.
Definition 3.2. Given a morphism $f$ in a FSSMC $\mathcal{C}$, a decomposition of $f$ consists in a set of morphism generators $\{f_{1},\dots,f_{n}\}$ such that $f$ is equal to a combination of compositions and monoidal products of identities, symmetries and the $f_{i}$, with each $f_{i}$ used at least once.
Definition 6.1. Let ${\mathcal{Q}}=(Q,\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}},I_{\mathcal{Q}},\circ_{\mathcal{Q}})$ be a quantale. A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category ${\mathcal{C}}$ consists of: (CD1): a set ${\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$ of objects; (CD2): for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$, an element ${\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime})\in{Q}$ satisfying the following axioms: (CA1): for each $c\in{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$, $I_{\mathcal{Q}}\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}{\mathcal{C}}(c,c)$; (CA2): for each $c,c^{\prime},c^{\prime\prime}\in{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$, ${\mathcal{C}}(c^{\prime},c^{\prime\prime})\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}{\mathcal{C}}(c,c% ^{\prime})\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}{\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime\prime})$. We also write $c\in{\mathcal{C}}$ for $c\in{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$.
Definition 3.1. Let ${\mathcal{Q}}$ be a quantale, and $A$ and $B$ be (possibly infinite) sets. A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-matrix (or simply a matrix) from $A$ to $B$ is a $(B\times A)$-indexed family of elements of $Q$. If $X=(X_{b,a})_{b\in B,a\in A}$ is a ${\mathcal{Q}}$-matrix from $A$ to $B$, we denote this by $X\colon A\mathrel{\mathchoice{\ooalign{$\displaystyle\mapstochar\mskip 5.0mu $% \cr$\displaystyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$\textstyle\mapstochar\mskip 5% .0mu $\cr$\textstyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$\scriptstyle\mapstochar% \mskip 5.0mu $\cr$\scriptstyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$% \scriptscriptstyle\mapstochar\mskip 5.0mu $\cr$\scriptscriptstyle% \longrightarrow$\cr}}}B$.
Definition 6.8. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category. The ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category $\mathrm{Isb}({\mathcal{C}})$ is defined as follows: (CA1): its set of objects is $\mathrm{Isb}({\mathcal{C}})$ as in Definition 4.1; (CA2): given $(X,Y)$ and $(X^{\prime},Y^{\prime})$ in $\mathrm{Isb}({\mathcal{C}})$, the element $\mathrm{Isb}({\mathcal{C}})((X,Y),(X^{\prime},Y^{\prime}))\in Q$ is defined as $\bigwedge_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}X^{\prime}_{\ast,c}\mathbin{\searrow}X_{\ast,c},$ or equivalently as $\bigwedge_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}Y^{\prime}_{c,\ast}\mathbin{\swarrow}Y_{c^{\prime% },\ast}.$ The ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $J_{\mathcal{C}}\colon{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow\mathrm{Isb}({\mathcal{C}})$ is defined by mapping each $c\in{\mathcal{C}}$ to $({\mathcal{C}}(c,-),{\mathcal{C}}(-,c))\in\mathrm{Isb}({\mathcal{C}})$, which turns out to be fully faithful. We call the pair $(\mathrm{Isb}({\mathcal{C}}),J_{\mathcal{C}})$ the Isbell completion of ${\mathcal{C}}$, and the ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $J_{\mathcal{C}}$ the Isbell embedding.
Definition 7.4 (Cf. [AHRT02, Definitions 2.1]). (1) A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $F\colon{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{D}}$ is called an essential embedding iff (i) $F$ is an embedding, and (ii) for any ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $G\colon{\mathcal{D}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{E}}$, if $G\circ F$ is an embedding then so is $G$. (2) An injective hull (or injective envelope) of a ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is a pair $({\mathcal{D}},F)$ consisting of an injective ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category ${\mathcal{D}}$ and an essential embedding $F\colon{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{D}}$.
Definition 5.1 ([CGQ04, Section 2.2]). Let ${\mathcal{Q}}=(Q,\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}},I_{\mathcal{Q}},\circ_{{\mathcal{Q}}})$ be a quantale. A (left) complete semimodule over ${\mathcal{Q}}$ is a complete lattice ${\mathcal{M}}=(M,\preceq_{{\mathcal{M}}})$ equipped with a left action $\ast_{{\mathcal{M}}}\colon Q\times M\longrightarrow M$ of the monoid $(Q,I_{\mathcal{Q}},\circ_{\mathcal{Q}})$ on the set $M$, such that $\ast_{\mathcal{M}}$ preserves arbitrary sups in each argument: $(\bigvee_{i\in I}x_{i})\ast_{\mathcal{M}}m=\bigvee_{i\in I}(x_{i}\ast_{% \mathcal{M}}m)$ and $x\ast_{\mathcal{M}}(\bigvee_{i\in I}m_{i})=\bigvee_{i\in I}(x\ast_{\mathcal{M}% }m_{i})$. A right complete semimodule over ${\mathcal{Q}}$ is a left complete semimodule over the quantale ${\mathcal{Q}}^{\mathrm{rev}}=(Q,\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}},I_{\mathcal{Q}},\circ^{% \mathrm{rev}}_{\mathcal{Q}})$, where $x\circ^{\mathrm{rev}}_{\mathcal{Q}}y=y\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}x$.
Definition 6.6 ([Stu05, Stu06]). A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is said to be: • tensored iff for any $x\in Q$ and $c\in{\mathcal{C}}$, a tensor product of $x$ and $c$ exists in ${\mathcal{C}}$; • cotensored iff for any $x\in Q$ and $c\in{\mathcal{C}}$, a cotensor product of $x$ and $c$ exists in ${\mathcal{C}}$; • order-compelete iff the preordered set $({\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})},\preceq_{\mathcal{C}})$ is complete (i.e., iff its poset reflection is a complete lattice); • complete iff it is tensored and order-complete.
Definition 2.1. A (unital) quantale ${\mathcal{Q}}$ is a complete lattice $(Q,\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}})$ equipped with a monoid structure $(Q,I_{\mathcal{Q}},\circ_{\mathcal{Q}})$ such that the multiplication $\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}$ preserves arbitrary sups in each argument: $(\bigvee_{i\in I}y_{i})\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}x=\bigvee_{i\in I}(y_{i}\circ_{% \mathcal{Q}}x)$ and $y\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}(\bigvee_{i\in I}x_{i})=\bigvee_{i\in I}(y\circ_{\mathcal{% Q}}x_{i})$. We often omit the subscript ${\mathcal{Q}}$ from the data of a quantale, writing it simply as ${\mathcal{Q}}=(Q,\preceq,I,\circ)$.
Definition 6.5. Let ${\mathcal{M}}=(M,\preceq_{\mathcal{M}},\ast_{{\mathcal{M}}})$ be a left complete semimodule over ${\mathcal{Q}}$. The following data defines a ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category, again called ${\mathcal{M}}$: (CD1): the set of objects is ${\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{M}})}=M$; and (CD2): for each $m,m^{\prime}\in M$, the element ${\mathcal{M}}(m,m^{\prime})\in Q$ is defined as $m^{\prime}\mathbin{\swarrow}_{\mathcal{M}}m$ (note the order of the arguments $m$ and $m^{\prime}$). The axioms can be checked easily by means of the adjointness relations (15).
Definition 7.1. A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category ${\mathcal{E}}$ is said to be injective (with respect to the embeddings) iff for any ${\mathcal{Q}}$-categories ${\mathcal{C}}$ and ${\mathcal{D}}$, any ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $F\colon{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{E}}$, and any embedding $G\colon{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{D}}$, there exists a (not necessarily unique) ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $H\colon{\mathcal{D}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{E}}$ such that $F=H\circ G$. ${\mathcal{C}}$${\mathcal{D}}$${\mathcal{E}}$$F$$G$$H$
Definition 4.1. Let ${\mathcal{Q}}$ be a quantale and $Z\colon A\mathrel{\mathchoice{\ooalign{$\displaystyle\mapstochar\mskip 5.0mu $% \cr$\displaystyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$\textstyle\mapstochar\mskip 5% .0mu $\cr$\textstyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$\scriptstyle\mapstochar% \mskip 5.0mu $\cr$\scriptstyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$% \scriptscriptstyle\mapstochar\mskip 5.0mu $\cr$\scriptscriptstyle% \longrightarrow$\cr}}}C$ be a ${\mathcal{Q}}$-matrix. The Isbell hull of $Z$, denoted by $\mathrm{Isb}(Z)$, is the set of all pairs $(X,Y)$ of ${\mathcal{Q}}$-matrices $X\colon A\mathrel{\mathchoice{\ooalign{$\displaystyle\mapstochar\mskip 5.0mu $% \cr$\displaystyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$\textstyle\mapstochar\mskip 5% .0mu $\cr$\textstyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$\scriptstyle\mapstochar% \mskip 5.0mu $\cr$\scriptstyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$% \scriptscriptstyle\mapstochar\mskip 5.0mu $\cr$\scriptscriptstyle% \longrightarrow$\cr}}}1$ and $Y\colon 1\mathrel{\mathchoice{\ooalign{$\displaystyle\mapstochar\mskip 5.0mu $% \cr$\displaystyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$\textstyle\mapstochar\mskip 5% .0mu $\cr$\textstyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$\scriptstyle\mapstochar% \mskip 5.0mu $\cr$\scriptstyle\longrightarrow$\cr}}{\ooalign{$% \scriptscriptstyle\mapstochar\mskip 5.0mu $\cr$\scriptscriptstyle% \longrightarrow$\cr}}}C$ such that both $Y=Z\mathbin{\swarrow}X$ and $X=Y\mathbin{\searrow}Z$ hold.
Definition 7.7. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category. The ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category $\mathcal{P}{\mathcal{C}}$ of presheaves over ${\mathcal{C}}$ is defined as follows. • An object is a presheaf over ${\mathcal{C}}$, that is a family $P=(Pc)_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}$ of elements of ${\mathcal{Q}}$ satisfying the inequality $Pc^{\prime}\circ{\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime})\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}Pc$ for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{C}}$. • The element $\mathcal{P}{\mathcal{C}}(P,P^{\prime})$ of ${\mathcal{Q}}$ is given by $\bigwedge_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}P^{\prime}c\mathbin{\swarrow}Pc$. Dually, the ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category $\mathcal{P}^{\dagger}{\mathcal{C}}$ of copresheaves over ${\mathcal{C}}$ is defined as follows. • An object is a copresheaf over ${\mathcal{C}}$, that is a family $R=(Rc)_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}$ of elements of ${\mathcal{Q}}$ satisfying the inequality ${\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime})\circ Rc\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}Rc^{\prime}$ for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{C}}$. • The element $\mathcal{P}^{\dagger}{\mathcal{C}}(R,R^{\prime})$ of ${\mathcal{Q}}$ is given by $\bigwedge_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}R^{\prime}c\mathbin{\searrow}Rc$.
Definition 6.7. Let ${\mathcal{Q}}$ be a quantale, and ${\mathcal{C}}$ and ${\mathcal{D}}$ be ${\mathcal{Q}}$-categories. (1) A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $F\colon{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{D}}$ is a function $F\colon{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}\longrightarrow{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{D}})}$ such that for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{C}}$, ${\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime})\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}{\mathcal{D}}(Fc,Fc^{\prime})$ holds. (2) A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $F$ is fully faithful iff for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{C}}$, (19) is satisfied with equality. We call fully faithful ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functors embeddings for short. (3) A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $F$ is bijective-on-objects iff the corresponding function $F\colon{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}\longrightarrow{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{D}})}$ is bijective. (4) A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $F$ is an isomorphism iff it is fully faithful and bijective-on-objects.
Definition 5.4. Let ${\mathcal{Q}}$ be a quantale and ${\mathcal{M}}=(M,\preceq_{{\mathcal{M}}},\ast_{{\mathcal{M}}})$ be a left complete semimodule over ${\mathcal{Q}}$. A left complete subsemimodule of ${\mathcal{M}}$ is a subset of $M$ closed under arbitrary sups in ${\mathcal{M}}$ and the tensor $x\ast_{\mathcal{M}}(-)$ by an arbitrary element $x\in Q$. A right complete subsemimodule of ${\mathcal{M}}$ is a subset of $M$ closed under arbitrary infs in ${\mathcal{M}}$ and the cotensor $x\mathbin{\searrow}_{\mathcal{M}}(-)$ by an arbitrary element $x\in Q$. We regard a left (resp. right) complete subsemimodule itself as a left (resp. right) complete semimodule, by the induced order and operation.
Definition 2.2.1. I. A couple of classes $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0},\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\subset\operatorname{Obj}% \underline{C}$ will be said to define a weight structure $w$ on a triangulated category $\underline{C}$ if they satisfy the following conditions. (i) $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ and $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ are retraction-closed in $\underline{C}$ (i.e., contain all $\underline{C}$-retracts of their objects). (ii) Semi-invariance with respect to translations. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\subset\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[1]$, $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]\subset\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$. (iii) Orthogonality. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\perp\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$. (iv) Weight decompositions. For any $M\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists a distinguished triangle $LM\to M\to RM{\to}LM[1]$ such that $LM\in\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $RM\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$.
Definition 1.2.2. 1. For any $i\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ we will use the notation $\underline{C}_{t\leq i}$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{t\geq i}$) for the class $\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}[i]$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}[i]$). 2. ${\underline{Ht}}$ is the full subcategory of $\underline{C}$ whose object class is $\underline{C}_{t=0}=\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}\cap\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}$. 3. We will say that $t$ is left (resp. right) non-degenerate if $\cap_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{t\geq i}=\{0\}$ (resp. $\cap_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}_{t\leq i}=\{0\}$). Moreover, we will say that $t$ is non-degenerate if it is both left and right non-degenerate. 4. We will say that $t$ is generated by a class $\mathcal{P}\subset\underline{C}$ whenever $\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}=(\cup_{i>0}\mathcal{P}[i]){}^{\perp}$.
Definition 2.1.1. For a sequence of objects $Y_{i}$ of $\underline{C}$ for $i\geq 0$ and maps $f_{i}:Y_{i}\to Y_{i+1}$ we consider the morphism $a:\oplus\operatorname{id}_{Y_{i}}\bigoplus\oplus(-f_{i}):D\to D$ (we can define it since its $i$-th component can be factorized into a composition $Y_{i}\to Y_{i}\bigoplus Y_{i+1}\to D$). Denote a cone of $a$ by $Y$. We will write $Y=\operatorname{\underrightarrow{\operatorname{holim}}}Y_{i}$ and call $Y$ a homotopy colimit of $Y_{i}$ (we will not consider any other homotopy colimits in this paper). Moreover, $\operatorname{\operatorname{Cone}}(f_{i})$ will be denoted by $Z_{i+1}$ and we set $Z_{0}=Y_{0}$.
Definition 3.3.1. Let $\underline{C}$ be a smashing triangulated category, and $\beta$ be a regular infinite cardinal (that is $\beta$ cannot be presented as a sum of less than $\beta$ cardinals that are less than $\beta$), $\mathcal{P}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$, and $\underline{\coprod}\mathcal{P}$ is the closure of $\mathcal{P}$ with respect to $\underline{C}$-coproducts. 1. An object $M$ of $\underline{C}$ is said to be $\beta$-small if for any small family $N_{i}\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ any morphism $M\to\coprod N_{i}$ factors through the coproduct of a subset of $\{N_{i}\}$ of cardinality less than $\beta$. 2. We will say that an object $M$ of $\underline{C}$ is $\beta$-compact if it belongs to the maximal perfect class of $\beta$-small objects of $\underline{C}$ (whose existence is immediate from Lemma 2.3.5(1)). We will write $\underline{C}^{\beta}$ for the full subcategory of $\underline{C}$ formed by $\beta$-compact objects. 3. We will say that $\underline{C}$ is $\beta$-well generated (or just well generated) if there exists a perfect set of $\beta$-small objects that generates $\underline{C}$ as its own localizing subcategory. 4. We will say that a class ${\tilde{\mathcal{P}}}$ of objects of $\underline{C}$ is $\beta$-coproductive if it is closed with respect to $\underline{C}$-coproducts of less than $\beta$ objects. 5. We will say that a torsion theory $s=(\mathcal{LO}^{\prime},\mathcal{RO}^{\prime})$ on a full triangulated subcategory $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ of $\underline{C}$ is $\beta$-coproductive if both $\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}^{\prime}$ and $\mathcal{RO}^{\prime}$ are $\beta$-coproductive. 6. We will say that $h\in\underline{C}(M,N)$ (for some $M,N\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$) is an $\mathcal{P}$-approximation (of $N$) if $h$ is $\mathcal{P}$-epic (see Definition 2.3.1(1)) and $M$ belongs to $\operatorname{Obj}\underline{\coprod}\mathcal{P}$. 7. We will say that $\mathcal{P}$ is contravariantly finite (in $\underline{C}$) if for any $N\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists its $\mathcal{P}$-approximation.13Actually, the standard convention is to say that $\underline{\coprod}\mathcal{P}$ is contravariantly finite if this condition is fulfilled; yet our version of this term is somewhat more convenient for the purposes of this section.
Definition 2.2.2. Let $i,j\in{\mathbb{Z}}$; assume that a triangulated category $\underline{C}$ is endowed with a weight structure $w$. 1. The full subcategory ${\underline{Hw}}$ of $\underline{C}$ whose objects are $\underline{C}_{w=0}=\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\cap\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ is called the heart of $w$. 2. $\underline{C}_{w\geq i}$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq i}$, resp. $\underline{C}_{w=i}$) will denote the class $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[i]$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[i]$, resp. $\underline{C}_{w=0}[i]$). 3. We will say that $w$ is (co)smashing if $\underline{C}$ is (co)smashing and the class $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ is (co)smashing in it. 4. Let $\underline{D}$ be a full triangulated subcategory of $\underline{C}$. We will say that $w$ restricts to $\underline{D}$ whenever the couple $(\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\cap\operatorname{Obj}\underline{D},\ \underline{C}_{w% \geq 0}\cap\operatorname{Obj}\underline{D})$ is a weight structure on $\underline{D}$. 5. We will say that a class $\mathcal{P}$ of objects of $\underline{C}$ generates $w$ whenever $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}=(\cup_{i>0}\mathcal{P}[-i]){}^{\perp}$. 6. We will say that $w$ is left (resp. right) adjacent to a $t$-structure $t$ on $\underline{C}$ if $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}=\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}$ (resp. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}=\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}$). Moreover, if this is the case we will also say that $t$ is right (resp. left) adjacent to $w$.
Definition 1.3.1. 1. We will say that a triangulated category $\underline{C}$ is (co)smashing if it is closed with respect to (small) coproducts (resp., products). 2. If $\underline{C}$ is (co)smashing and $\mathcal{P}$ is a class of objects of $\underline{C}$ then we will say that $\mathcal{P}$ is (co)smashing (in $\underline{C}$) if it is closed with respect to $\underline{C}$-coproducts (resp., $\underline{C}$-products). 3. If $\underline{C}$ is smashing and $\underline{D}$ is a triangulated subcategory of $\underline{C}$ that may be equal to $\underline{C}$, one says that $\mathcal{P}$ generates $\underline{D}$ as a localizing subcategory of $\underline{C}$ if $\underline{D}$ is the smallest strictly full triangulated subcategory of $\underline{C}$ that contains $\mathcal{P}$ and is closed with respect to $\underline{C}$-coproducts. 4. It will be convenient for us to use the following somewhat clumsy terminology: a homological functor $H:\underline{C}\to\underline{A}$ (where $\underline{A}$ is an abelian category) will be called a cc (resp. wcc) functor if it respects all coproducts (resp. countable coproducts, i.e., the image of any countable coproduct diagram in $\underline{C}$ is the corresponding coproduct diagram in $\underline{A}$), whereas a cohomological functor $H^{\prime}$ from $\underline{C}$ into $\underline{A}$ will be called a cp functor if it converts all (small) coproducts that exist in $\underline{C}$ into the corresponding $\underline{A}$-products. 5. We will say that a smashing category $\underline{C}$ satisfies the Brown representability property whenever any cp functor from $\underline{C}$ into abelian groups is representable. 6. An object $M$ of a smashing category $\underline{C}$ is said to be compact if the functor $H^{M}=\underline{C}(M,-):\underline{C}\to\operatorname{Ab}$ respects coproducts. We will write $\underline{C}^{{\aleph_{0}}}$ for the full subcategory of $\underline{C}$ whose objects are the compact objects of $\underline{C}$; note that $\underline{C}^{{\aleph_{0}}}$ is triangulated according to (the easy) Lemma 4.1.4 of [Nee01]. 7. We will say that $\mathcal{P}$ compactly generates (a smashing category) $\underline{C}$ and that $\underline{C}$ is compactly generated if $\mathcal{P}$ generates $\underline{C}$ as its own localizing subcategory and $\mathcal{P}$ is a set of compact objects of $\underline{C}$. 8. We will say that a $t$-structure $t$ on $\underline{C}$ is (co)smashing if $\underline{C}$ is (co)smashing and the class $\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}$ is smashing (resp., $\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}$ is cosmashing). 9. We will say that $t$ as above is compactly generated (by $\mathcal{P}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$) if $\mathcal{P}$ is a set of compact objects.
Definition 1.2.1. A couple of subclasses $\underline{C}_{t\leq 0},\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}\subset\operatorname{Obj}% \underline{C}$ will be said to be a $t$-structure $t$ on $\underline{C}$ if they satisfy the following conditions: (i) $\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}$ and $\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}$ are strict, i.e., contain all objects of $\underline{C}$ isomorphic to their elements. (ii) $\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}\subset\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}[1]$ and $\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}[1]\subset\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}$. (iii) $\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}[1]\perp\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}$. (iv) For any $M\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists a $t$-decomposition distinguished triangle $L_{t}M\to M\to R_{t}M{\to}L_{t}M[1]$ such that $L_{t}M\in\underline{C}_{t\geq 0},R_{t}M\in\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}[-1]$. 2. ${\underline{Ht}}$ is the full subcategory of $\underline{C}$ whose object class is $\underline{C}_{t=0}=\underline{C}_{t\leq 0}\cap\underline{C}_{t\geq 0}$.
Definition 3.1.1. 1. A couple $s$ of classes $\mathcal{LO},\mathcal{RO}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ will be said to be a torsion theory (on $\underline{C}$) if $\mathcal{LO}^{\perp}=\mathcal{RO}$, $\mathcal{LO}={}^{\perp}\mathcal{RO}$, and for any $M\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists a distinguished triangle $L_{s}M\stackrel{{\scriptstyle a_{M}}}{{\to}}M\stackrel{{\scriptstyle n_{M}}}{{% \to}}R_{s}M{\to}L_{s}M[1]$ such that $L_{s}M\in\mathcal{LO}$ and $R_{s}M\in\mathcal{RO}$. We will call any triangle of this form an $s$-decomposition of $M$; $a_{M}$ will be called an $s$-decomposition morphism. 2. We will say (following [PoS16, Definition 3.1]) that $s$ is generated by $\mathcal{P}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ if $\mathcal{P}^{\perp}=\mathcal{RO}$. Moreover, if $\mathcal{P}$ is a set of compact objects then we will say that $s$ is compactly generated. 3. We will say that $s$ is (co)smashing if $\underline{C}$ is (co)smashing and $\mathcal{RO}$ is smashing (resp. $\mathcal{LO}$ is cosmashing) in it. 4. If $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ is a full triangulated subcategory of $\underline{C}$ then we will say that $s$ restricts to it whenever $(\mathcal{LO}\cap\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}^{\prime},\mathcal{RO}\cap% \operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}^{\prime})$ is a torsion theory on $\underline{C}^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.1.4. 1. A class ${\tilde{\mathcal{P}}}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ will be called strongly extension-closed if it contains $0$ and for any $f_{i}:Y_{i}\to Y_{i+1}$ such that $Y_{0}\in{\tilde{\mathcal{P}}}$ and $\operatorname{\operatorname{Cone}}(f_{i})\in{\tilde{\mathcal{P}}}$ for all $i\geq 0$ we have $\operatorname{\varinjlim}_{i\geq 0}Y_{i}\in{\tilde{\mathcal{P}}}$ (i.e. ${\tilde{\mathcal{P}}}$ contains all possible cones of the corresponding distinguished triangle; note that these are isomorphic). 2. The smallest strongly extension-closed retraction-closed class of objects of $\underline{C}$ that contains a class $\mathcal{P}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ and is closed with respect to arbitrary $\underline{C}$-coproducts will be called the strong extension-closure of $\mathcal{P}$. 3. We will write $\underline{\coprod}\mathcal{P}$ either for the closure of $\mathcal{P}$ with respect to $\underline{C}$-coproducts or for the full subcategory of $\underline{C}$ formed by these objects. Also, we will call the class of the objects of $\underline{C}$ that may be presented as homotopy limits of $Y_{i}$ with $Y_{0}$ and $\operatorname{\operatorname{Cone}}(f_{i})\in\underline{\coprod}\mathcal{P}$ the naive big hull of $\mathcal{P}$. We will call the retraction-closure of the naive big hull of the class $\mathcal{P}$ its big hull.
Definition 2.3.1. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a class of objects of $\underline{C}$. 1. We will say that a $\underline{C}$-morphism $h$ is $\mathcal{P}$-null (resp. $\mathcal{P}$-epic) whenever for all $M\in\mathcal{P}$ we have $H^{M}(h)=0$ (resp. $H^{M}(h)$ is surjective), where $H^{M}=\underline{C}(M,-):\underline{C}\to\operatorname{Ab}$. We will write $\mathcal{P}-\mathbf{null}$ for the class of all $\mathcal{P}$-null morphisms. 2. Assume that $\underline{C}$ is smashing. Then we will say that $\mathcal{P}$ is (countably) perfect if the class $\mathcal{P}-\mathbf{null}$ is closed with respect to (countable) $\underline{C}$-coproducts.
Definition 3.2.1 (F. p. prosemimonoidal structure). An f. p. prosemimonoidal structure on $\mathbf{A}$ consist of the following data: (1) A bilinear functor $T\colon\mathbf{A}\times\mathbf{A}\to\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (f. p. protensor product). (2) An isomorphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{\Pi}}_{a,b,c}\colon a\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}\left(b\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}c\right)\xrightarrow{\sim}\left(% a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}b\right)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}c$ natural in $a,b,c\in\mathbf{A}$ (f. p. proassociator). This data is subject to the condition that the following diagram commutes for all $a,b,c,d\in\mathbf{A}$ (restricted pentagon identity): $a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(b% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(c% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}d))$$(a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}b)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(c% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}d)$$a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}((b% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}c)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}d)$$((a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}b)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}c)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}d$$(a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(b% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}c))% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}d$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{a,b,c}\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}d$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{a,b\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}c,d}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{a\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}b,c,d}$$a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{b,c,d}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{a,b,c\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}d}$$\circlearrowleft$
Definition 3.2.6 (F. p. prointernal hom). An f. p. prointernal hom structure on $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ is an f. p. promonoidal structure together with the following data: (1) For every $a\in\mathbf{A}$, an additive functor $\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}(a,-):\mathbf{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (f. p. prointernal hom). (2) For every $a\in\mathbf{A}$, a morphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{coev}}_{b,a}:b\longrightarrow\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}(a,% b\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}a)$ natural in $b\in\mathbf{A}$ (f. p. procoevaluation). (3) For every $a\in\mathbf{A}$, a morphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{ev}}_{a,b}:\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}(a,b)\operatorname{% \otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}a\longrightarrow b$ natural in $b\in\mathbf{A}$ (f. p. proevaluation). As usual, the extensions of these data to the Freyd category $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ are denoted by $\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(a,-)$, $\widehat{\mathrm{coev}}_{-,a}$ and $\widehat{\mathrm{ev}}_{a,-}$, respectively. Baring this notation in mind, the data is moreover subject to the condition that the restrictions of Equation 6 and Equation 7 to $\mathbf{A}$ commute.
Definition 3.1.3 (Braided monoidal structure). A monoidal structure on $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ together with a natural isomorphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{A,B}:A\operatorname{\otimes% _{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B\xrightarrow{\sim}B% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A$ (braiding) for $A,B\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ is called a braided monoidal structure if the following diagrams commute for all $A,B,C\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$: • compatibility with left- and right unitor $A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}1$$1\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A$$A$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{A,1}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Psi}$}}}_{A}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Omega}$}}}_{A}$$\circlearrowleft$ • hexagonal identity I: $(A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C$$C\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(A% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)$$A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(B% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C)$$(C\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B$$A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(C% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)$$(A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{A\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B,C}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{C,A,B}$$(\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{C,A}\operatorname{\otimes_% {\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}\mathrm{id}_{B})$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}^{-1}_{A,B,C}$$(\mathrm{id}_{A}\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T% }$}}}}}\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{B,C})$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{A,C,B}$$\circlearrowleft$ • hexagonal identity II: $A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(B% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C)$$(B\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A$$(A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C$$B\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(C% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A)$$(B\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C$$B\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(A% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C)$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{A,B\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}^{-1}_{B,C,A}$$\mathrm{id}_{B}\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}% $}}}}}\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{C,A}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{A,B,C}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{A,B}\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}\mathrm{id}_{C}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}^{-1}_{B,A,C}$$\circlearrowleft$
Definition 3.2.4 (F. p. braided promonoidal structure). An f. p. promonoidal structure on an additive category $\mathbf{A}$ together with a natural isomorphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{\Gamma}}_{a,b}:a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{% \mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}b\xrightarrow{{\sim}}b\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}a$ (f. p. probraiding) for $a,b\in\mathbf{A}$ is called an f. p. braided promonoidal structure if the restrictions of Equation 3, Equation 4 and Equation 5 to $\mathbf{A}$ commute.
Definition 3.1.5 (Internal hom structure). An internal hom structure on $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ is a monoidal structure together with the following data: (1) For every $A\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$, an additive functor $\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(A,-):\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})\rightarrow% \mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (internal hom). (2) For every $B\in\mathbf{A}$, a morphism $\widehat{\mathrm{coev}}_{A,B}:A\longrightarrow\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}% }}(B,A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)$ natural in $A\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (coevaluation). (3) For every $A\in\mathbf{A}$, a morphism $\widehat{\mathrm{ev}}_{A,B}:\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(A,B)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A\longrightarrow B$ natural in $B\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (evaluation). This data is subject to the condition that $A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B$$\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(B,A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{% \mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm% {\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B$$A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B$$\widehat{\mathrm{coev}}_{A,B}\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{% \text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B$$\widehat{\mathrm{ev}}_{B,A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$% \widehat{T}$}}}}}B}$$\mathrm{id}$ and $\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(A,B)$$\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}\left(A,\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(A% ,B)\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A\right)$$\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(A,B)$$\widehat{\mathrm{coev}}_{\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(A,B),A}$$\widehat{\underline{\mathrm{Hom}}}(A,\widehat{\mathrm{ev}}_{A,B})$$\mathrm{id}$ commute for all $A,B\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$.
Definition 3.1.1 (Semimonoidal structure). A semimonoidal structure on $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ consist of the following data: (1) A bilinear functor $\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}\colon% \mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})\times\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})\to\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (tensor product). (2) An isomorphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{A,B,C}\colon A\operatorname{% \otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(B\operatorname{\otimes% _{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C)\xrightarrow{\sim}(A% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C$ natural in $A,B,C\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (associator). This data is subject to the condition that the following diagram commutes for all $A,B,C,D\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (pentagon identity): $A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(B% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(C% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}D))$$(A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(C% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}D)$$A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}((B% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}D)$$((A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}D$$(A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(B% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C))% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}D$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{A,B,C}\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}D$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{A,B\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}C,D}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{A\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B,C,D}$$A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{B,C,D}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{A,B,C\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}D}$$\circlearrowleft$
Definition 3.2.3 (F. p. promonoidal structure). An f. p. promonoidal structure on $\mathbf{A}$ is an f. p. prosemimonoidal structure on $\mathbf{A}$ together with (1) an object $1\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (f. p. protensor unit), (2) an isomorphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{\Psi}}_{a}\colon 1\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{% \mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}a\xrightarrow{\sim}a$ natural in $a\in\mathbf{A}$ (f. p. left prounitor), (3) an isomorphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{\Omega}}_{a}\colon a\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname% {\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}1\xrightarrow{\sim}a$ natural in $a\in\mathbf{A}$ (f. p. right prounitor), such that the restriction of the triangle identity Equation 2 to $\mathbf{A}$ commutes.
Definition 3.1.4 (Symmetric monoidal structure). A braided monoidal structure on $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ with the property $\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{A,B}=\operatorname{\mathrm{% \text{$\widehat{\Gamma}$}}}_{B,A}^{-1}$ for $A,B\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ is called a symmetric monoidal structure.
Definition 2.2.1. We call an $n$-ary functor $F:\mathbf{A}_{1}\times\dots\times\mathbf{A}_{n}\rightarrow\mathbf{B}$ which is componentwise additive a multilinear functor. Moreover, if $\mathbf{A}_{1},\dots,\mathbf{A}_{n},\mathbf{B}$ have cokernels, we say that $F$ is right exact if it is componentwise right exact, i.e., if for all $k\in\{1,\dots,n\}$ the natural morphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{coker}}\left(F(a_{1},\dots,a_{k-1},\alpha_{k},a_{k+1},% \dots,a_{n})\right)\longrightarrow F\left(a_{1},\dots,a_{k-1},\operatorname{% \mathrm{coker}}(\alpha_{k}),a_{k+1},\dots,a_{n}\right)$ is an isomorphism for all objects $a_{i}\in\mathbf{A}_{i}$, $i\neq k$, and all morphisms $\alpha_{k}\in\mathbf{A}_{k}$.
Definition 2.1.1. The Freyd category $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ consists of the following data: (1) Objects are given by morphisms in $\mathbf{A}$. (2) Morphisms from $(a\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\rho}}{{\longleftarrow}}r)$ to $(a^{\prime}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\rho^{\prime}}}{{\longleftarrow}}r^{\prime})$ are given by morphisms $a\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\alpha}}{{\longrightarrow}}a^{\prime}$ in $\mathbf{A}$ such that there exists another morphism $r\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\omega}}{{\longrightarrow}}r^{\prime}$ rendering the diagram $a$$r$$a^{\prime}$$r^{\prime}$$\rho$$\rho^{\prime}$$\alpha$$\omega$ commutative. The morphism $\alpha$ is called the morphism datum and any possible $\omega$ a morphism witness. We write $\{\alpha\}$ or $\{\alpha,\omega\}$ for a morphism in $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{P})$, depending on whether we would like to highlight a particular choice of a morphism witness. Given another morphism $\{\alpha^{\prime}\}$ from $(a\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\rho}}{{\longleftarrow}}r)$ to $(a^{\prime}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\rho^{\prime}}}{{\longleftarrow}}r^{\prime})$, we define it to be equal in $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{P})$ to $\{\alpha\}$ if there exists a $\lambda:a\rightarrow r^{\prime}$ such that $(\alpha-\alpha^{\prime})=\lambda\cdot\rho^{\prime}.$ Any such $\lambda$ is called a witness for $\alpha$ and $\alpha^{\prime}$ being equal. (3) Composition, identities, and the additive structure are inherited from $\mathbf{A}$.
Definition 3.1.2 (Monoidal structure). A monoidal structure on $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ is a semimonoidal structure on $\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ together with (1) an object $1\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (tensor unit), (2) a natural isomorphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Psi}$}}}_{A}\colon 1\operatorname{% \otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}A\xrightarrow{\sim}A$ (left unitor), (3) and a natural isomorphism $\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Omega}$}}}_{A}\colon A\operatorname{% \otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}1\xrightarrow{\sim}A$ (right unitor) such that the following diagram commutes for all $A,B\in\mathcal{A}(\mathbf{A})$ (triangle identity): $A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}(1% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B)$$(A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}1)% \operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B$$A\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}B$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Pi}$}}}_{A,1,B}$$\mathrm{id}_{A}\operatorname{\otimes_{\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}% $}}}}}\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Psi}$}}}_{B}$$\operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{\Omega}$}}}_{A}\operatorname{\otimes_{% \operatorname{\mathrm{\text{$\widehat{T}$}}}}}\mathrm{id}_{B}$$\circlearrowleft$
Definition 3.2.5 (Symmetric f. p. promonoidal structure). An f. p. braided promonoidal structure on an additive category $\mathbf{A}$ with the property $\operatorname{\mathrm{\Gamma}}_{a,b}=\operatorname{\mathrm{\Gamma}}_{b,a}^{-1}$ for all $a,b\in\mathbf{A}$ is called a symmetric f. p. promonoidal structure.
Definition 2.2. Objects of the category $\mathbf{T}$ are pairs $(A,\mathcal{R})$, where $A$ is a set and $\mathcal{R}$ is a family of subsets of $A$. A morphism $f:(A,\mathcal{R})\rightarrow(B,\mathcal{S})$ is a mapping $f:A\rightarrow B$ such that $f^{-1}[S]\in\mathcal{R}$ for all $S\in\mathcal{S}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $F:\mathbf{Set}\rightarrow\mathbf{Set}$ be a set functor and $\kappa$ a cardinal. $F$ is $\kappa$-accessible if $FY=\bigcup\{Ff[FX]\,;\,|X|<\kappa,f:X\rightarrow Y\}$ for every set $X$. A set functor $F$ is accessible if it is $\kappa$-accessible for some $\kappa$, and $F$ is finitary if it is $\aleph_{0}$-accessible.
Definition 3.3. Let $A$ be an augmented dg algebra, and let $\widecheck{B}A$ be its extended bar construction. Let $\xi\in\operatorname{MC}(A\otimes\widecheck{B}A)$ be the canonical Maurer–Cartan element corresponding to the counit $\Omega\widecheck{B}A\to A$ of the adjunction $\Omega\dashv\widecheck{B}$. Define a pair of functors $G\colon(\mathsf{pcDGMod}\textrm{-}\widecheck{B}A)^{\mathrm{op}}% \rightleftarrows\mathsf{DGMod}\textrm{-}A\nobreak\mskip 6.0mu plus 1.0mu % \mathpunct{}\nonscript\mskip-3.0mu {:}\mskip 2.0mu F$ as follows. The functor $F$ associates to a dg $A$-module $M$ the pseudocompact dg $\widecheck{B}A$-module $FM\coloneqq(M^{*}\otimes\widecheck{B}A)^{[\xi]}$ and the functor $G$ associates to a pseudocompact dg $\widecheck{B}A$-module $N$ the dg $A$-module $GN\coloneqq(N^{*}\otimes A)^{[\xi]}.$
Definition 4.2. Let $A$ be a curved dg algebra with a retraction $\epsilon\colon A\to k$. The extended bar construction of $A$ is the graded pseudocompact algebra $\widecheck{B}A\coloneqq\widecheck{T}\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}.$ Then by 2.2(1), the identity on $\widecheck{T}\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}$ induces a map $i\colon B^{\prime}A\cong T^{\prime}(\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*})\to\widecheck{B% }A\cong\widecheck{T}(\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*})$, and we define the differential $d_{\widecheck{B}A}$ on $\widecheck{B}A$ to be $d_{\widecheck{B}A}:=i\circ\xi_{1}\colon\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}\to T^{\prime% }(\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*})\to\widecheck{T}(\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}).$ The curvature of $\widecheck{B}A$ is the image of the curvature in $B^{\prime}A$ under the map $i\colon B^{\prime}A\to\widecheck{B}A$. This gives $\widecheck{B}A$ the structure of a curved pseudocompact dg algebra.
Definition 3.1. Let $(A,d_{A})$ be a dg algebra and $x\in\operatorname{MC}(A)$. (1) The twisted algebra of $A$ by $x$, denoted $A^{x}=(A,d^{x})$, is the dg algebra with the same underlying algebra as $A$ and differential $d^{x}(a)=d_{A}(a)+[x,a]$. (2) Let $(M,d_{M})$ be a left dg $A$-module. The twisted module of $M$ by $x$, denoted $M^{[x]}=(M,d^{[x]})$, is the left dg $A^{x}$-module with the same underlying module structure as $M$ and differential $d^{[x]}(m)=d(m)+xm$.
Definition 2.5. We define a pair of functors $\Omega\colon(\mathsf{pcDGA}^{*})^{\mathrm{op}}\rightleftarrows\mathsf{DGA}^{*}% \nobreak\mskip 6.0mu plus 1.0mu \mathpunct{}\nonscript\mskip-3.0mu {:}\mskip 2% .0mu \widecheck{B}$ as follows. The cobar construction associates to a pseudocompact dg algebra $C$ the dg algebra $\Omega C\coloneqq T\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{C}^{*}$ with differential defined in the usual way. The extended bar construction associates to a dg algebra $A$ the pseudocompact dg algebra $\widecheck{B}A\coloneqq\widecheck{T}\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}.$ We define the differential on $\widecheck{B}A$ as follows: Let $d_{1}\colon\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}\to\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}$ and $d_{2}\colon\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}\to\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}\widehat{% \otimes}\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}$ be induced by dualising the differential and multiplication on $A$ respectively. For a pseudocompact vector space $V$, consider the semi-completed tensor algebra $T^{\prime}(V)=\bigoplus_{n\geq 1}V^{\widehat{\otimes}n}$, which has a topology that is neither pseudocompact nor discrete, and has the property $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{Alg}}(T^{\prime}(V),B)\cong\operatorname{Hom}(V,B)$ for any pseudocompact algebra $B$ (see [Gua, Lemma 4.5]). Then by 2.2(1), the identity on $\widecheck{T}\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}$ induces a map $i\colon T^{\prime}(\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*})\to\widecheck{T}(\Sigma^{-1}% \widebar{A}^{*})$, and we define the differential to be $i\circ(d_{1}+d_{2})\colon\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}\to T^{\prime}(\Sigma^{-1}% \widebar{A}^{*})\to\widecheck{T}(\Sigma^{-1}\widebar{A}^{*}).$
Definition 3.2. A twisted $A$-module is a dg $A$-module that is free as an $A$-module after forgetting the differential, that is, it is isomorphic as an $A$-module to $V\otimes A$ for some graded vector space $V$. A finitely generated twisted $A$-module is a twisted $A$-module $V\otimes A$ with $V$ finite-dimensional.
Definition 2.1. Let $V$ be a pseudocompact graded vector space. If $V$ is finite-dimensional, its pseudocompact tensor algebra $\widecheck{T}V$ is the pseudocompact completion of the tensor algebra $TV$. For a general pseudocompact vector space $V=\mathop{\mathchoice{\varlim@\displaystyle{\leftarrowfill@\scriptstyle}}{% \varlim@\textstyle{\leftarrowfill@\scriptstyle}}{\varlim@\scriptstyle{% \leftarrowfill@\scriptstyle}}{\varlim@\scriptscriptstyle{\leftarrowfill@% \scriptstyle}}}\displaylimits_{i}V_{i}$, its pseudocompact tensor algebra is $\widecheck{T}V\coloneqq\mathop{\mathchoice{\varlim@\displaystyle{% \leftarrowfill@\scriptstyle}}{\varlim@\textstyle{\leftarrowfill@\scriptstyle}}% {\varlim@\scriptstyle{\leftarrowfill@\scriptstyle}}{\varlim@\scriptscriptstyle% {\leftarrowfill@\scriptstyle}}}\displaylimits_{i}{\widecheck{T}V_{i}}.$
Definition 3.5. Let $C$ be a dg coalgebra. A dg $C$-comodule is coacyclic if it is in the minimal triangulated subcategory of the homotopy category of dg $C$-comodules containing the total $C$-comodules of exact triples of dg $C$-comodules and closed under infinite direct sums.
Definition 1.1. For an additive category $\mathscr{C}$ and its category of chain complexes $C(\mathscr{C})$ , let $X=\{X^{i},d_{X}^{i}\}$ and $Y=\{Y^{i},d_{Y}^{i}\}$ be (co)chain complexes in $C(\mathscr{C})$ and $f$ and $g$ be morphisms of (co)chain complex in $C(\mathscr{C})(X,Y)$. A homotopy $\Psi$ from $f$ to $g$ is a sequence of morphisms $\Psi=\{\Psi^{i}:X^{i}\to Y^{i}\}$ that satisfies $\displaystyle f^{i}-g^{i}=d^{i-1}_{Y}\circ\Psi^{i}+\Psi^{i+1}\circ d^{i}_{X}$ for all $i\in\mathbb{Z}$. For this homotopy, homotopy equivalent is defined as follows. Definition 1.2. If (co)chain complexes $X$ and $Y\in ob(C(\mathscr{C}))$ are isomorphic in a homotopy category $K(\mathscr{C})$, then $X$ and $Y$ are said to be homotopy equivalent, denoted by $X\simeq Y$. That is, these exist homotopies $\Psi$ and $\Phi$ for $f\in C(\mathscr{C})(X,Y)$ and $g\in C(\mathscr{C})(Y,X)$ which satisfy the condition $\displaystyle g\circ f\underset{\Psi}{\sim}id_{X},\quad f\circ g\underset{\Phi% }{\sim}id_{Y}.$ See Chapter $3$ of [homological] for details on these definitions. In this paper, the symbol $\simeq$ is used to mean homotopy equivalent. The goal of this article is to show if $V$ is a commutative ring $R$ then $\lambda$ is the sequence of the homology groups of $R$ coefficients of a chain complex $F$ in $(\ref{ev})$.
